{
  "title": "Storycrafts",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "ce030c6e4dabdaa8",
      "text": "*Les Traceurs* is a game that allows you to collaboratively **produce the Story** of an event (be it a meeting, a conference, a workshop, a festival, a web-festival, etc...), almost live, and to **disseminate it** to the relevant federations and communities across the Internets."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "1b865b32e2a83492",
      "text": "The game is a production of Les Ã‰thers Fertiles and is released in public domain for anyone to be able to use it, remix it, distirbute it, sell it as one wishes, as long as the authors are mentioned."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "520290502a36a7e0",
      "text": "It is a hybrid game, in the sense there is both a physical aspect to it (a printed game with cards, a board, a specific timing,...) and a digital one (you complete your action cards online using specific digital tools, generally free and opensource software ones, that we technically call micro-services). EACH PERSON SHOULD PUT ITS OWN STYLE INTO ITS CREATION!"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "5c8ba89ca187050f",
      "text": "# Let's play"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "804676f5aee45639",
      "text": "- Duration of a game: generally 1h15 to 4 hours\n- Amount of players: 3 to 8.\n- Goal: collaboratively produce a maximum of *Traces*."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "f5bfc5b45db47d0e",
      "text": "**What is a *Trace*?**\n\nA *Trace* is a key concept of this game. Indeed, a *Trace* represents any micro-task that a player does more or less in that way:\n- 1: listening to what is going \n- 2: isolating a bit of it\n- 3: translating it into a symbol,a piece of information, or a piece of language (for example: a text sentence, an image, a live sketching or an audio recording)\n- 4: sharing it with the world in an understandable fashion"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "666e22ed9468b0ba",
      "text": "In other words, we could describe a *Trace* as a **micro-gift to the commons.**"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "b5a80097e5b0eeb5",
      "text": "*Trace* is a French word that is relatively similar in  meaning to an *impression* or a *stamp* in English, in the way that Gutenberg's fellows were printing out books in the 15th century, or in the way that the Sumerians were writing symbols on clay stones around 3,000 BC.  "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "742831d8d9e4bc10",
      "text": "# "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "c24d17a4d4cb8ae9",
      "text": "#(un)Rules of the game"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "e7d55fd675a517a2",
      "text": "- Shuffle and get 1 Role card with its related Action cards (need two Scribes minimum, quite always) - You will be able to keep track of the *Traces* you have produced anytime you have completed the task written on one of your Action cards, on the Action card itself or by moving the pearls of your handwrist, in the same way Chinese people were using their abacus to do the maths for their accounting)\n- You can form a duo of players with another player if you do not feeling too comfortable with your role at first (and please remember that this is just a game: so trying and making mistakes is simply awesome).\n- First round: 22'22s during which each players produces a maximum of *Traces*\n- First 6'66s break: players gather in a not too noisy spot where they can have a good conversation about the Traces and symbols they have created so far: *\"how fun has it been for each one of us? Are there action cards that were difficult to complete? Should we focus on some action cards that we have undersued so far? Where are the gaps? Can we see the start of a beautifully documented story? Is the pollination aspect looking promising in terms of potential conversations it could trigger?\"*. Once the time has elapsed, each player goes back to its role (let us not change role yet, let us first play and explore and push the possibilities of each one's role a bit more :-)\n- Second round: 33'33s during which each players produces a maximum of *Traces*.\n- Second 6'66s break: same as first break, except that a the end of the break, the players who wish to change role can out back their Role card and its related Action cards in the stack of cards, and randomly receive a new Role card. Players who want to stick with their first Role can do so.\n- Third round: same, but lasts 44'44s.\nAnd so on, til the event ends up. At the end of the event, players can gather and have a look at the result of their collaboratively crafted Story, and help catalyze the dissemination of it through the relevant conversational channels identified by the Pollinator."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "75ea1457dc5dc1e6",
      "text": "# The roles           \n- **The Scribe** : is the one who's writing the content. He/she is collecting all the information/content about the event and he /she retrancripts by writing text. The writing style is up to him/her (crazy lyrical, frowning essay, cold meeting minutes, hot poetry). There are usually 2 scribes for each game.\n            \n- **The Iconographer** : it is the person who is in charge to illustrate the event. His/her task is to find on the Internet or to take picture of the event and to select the more appropriate to illustrate what's the scribe is writing. this role have also the job to put the right references about the picture (author...).\n            \n- **The Empathetic-Skeptic** : this person is the one who criticize or congratulate some element or content about the event. \n            \n- **The Sourcerer** : this role involves someone to double check all the information (Scribe and the empathetic-skeptic). He/she have to find articles, conversations, forum about the topic about and try to find and complete the writing by good sources, and if there is a polemic,  try to find what is about)\n            \n- **The Pollinator** : this role have 2 (or 3)task : \n                -finds conversational spaces (forums, chats, specific #hashtags,...) where the topic is actively  discussed by a bunch of people\n                -does a mapping of those conversatinal spaces (Note: *there is a useful resource at newspeak house, which is a list of all tech or political groups related to their topic democracy+technology+art*\n\n                -posts comments or tweets on the go, every hour or so, with a link to the Story that is being crafted -even though it is not complete-, making sure that it is actually relating to the interests of the people of the particular conversational space. He can then invite them to join the production by sending them one of the remaining Role cards, or simply the final result of the Story\n                -follows-up with the posts he made during the week that follows the event, to keep the conversation on and help it grow.  \n    \n- **The Summarian** (Animator): \n     -collects all the contents and makes them coherent with each others, especially by summarizing them \n(be it through drawings, text or audio format) and by proposing an esthetics to put them altogether. \n  \n- **The Audio Poet**: \n    -runs 2' interviews with the participants of the event to fuel the Story with different voices and viewpoints\n    -*Sina to invent and propose playful easy to make audio formats* \n \n- **The Newage Mapper**:\n    -proposes insightful visualizations (be them digital datavisualization or handmade drawings) to give the future readers of the Story a sense of the atmosphere, spirit and mood of the event\n\n- **The 5Sense Translator**: translates all the contents into a sign language fashion."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "6bac4630af12f305",
      "text": "# Are certain tasks worth a different amount of Traces?\n\nIt is up to the Summarian (who is also the Animator of the game), to discuss that with the players, according to the general esthetics and to the contents they wish to produce altogether."
    }
